This paper is likely to belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category as it proposes a new MAC protocol for multiuser MIMO (MU-MIMO) LANs. It also involves the use of traditional 802.11 CSMA/CA for contention-based transmission opportunities. 

It could also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category as it deals with maximizing the throughput gain of MU-MIMO while ensuring fairness among users. 

The cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category is also a possibility as MU-MIMO is often used in multimedia applications that require high throughput and low latency. 

The cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category could be relevant as the proposed protocol involves matching users based on their channel characteristics, which could be seen as a control problem. 

Finally, the cs.AR (Hardware Architecture) sub-category could be relevant as the paper mentions a prototype implementation using USRP N200, which is a hardware platform for software-defined radio.
